      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i have a physics exam coming up and i'm struggling a bit with the concept of quantum entanglement. can you give me a concise, non-mathematical summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a mind-bending concept where two or more particles become linked in such a way that they share the same fate, no matter how far apart they are. Imagine you have two of those perfectly matched, yet utterly unpredictable, magical coins—the very instant you check one and see it's heads, you *instantly* know the other one, even if it's across the galaxy, must be tails. This instantaneous connection is the core of entanglement, and it's weirder than any simple agreement between two regular, predictable, and non-magical, everyday objects. The difference from classical correlation is that in the classical world, the coins *already had* a determined state before you looked; the correlation was just hidden information, not a fundamental link. In the quantum world, the particles genuinely *don't* have a definite state until the moment one is measured, and that measurement instantaneously forces the state of the other.",
